Add integration test for gazebo_yarp_controlboard plugin  (#529) * Add integration test for gazebo_yarp_controlboard plugin

Add basic integration test for the position control and the velocity control.
The test simulates a simple one dof model (a pendulum) with a joint actuated
by a gazebo_yarp_controlboard, and uses the remote_controlboard and the controlboardwrapper2
to specify a position first and velocity setpoint later, and verify that the
simulated robot reaches the requested setpoints. To avoid the need to
run the yarpserver externally, the test uses YARP in local mode.

Fix handling of velocityControlImplementationType option in gazebo_yarp_controlboard The option was added in https://github.com/robotology/gazebo-yarp-plugins/pull/514
and it is meant to be present in the VELOCITY_CONTROL group, but before this fix it was
checked as part of the global plugin parameter space.
Merge pull request #514 from robotology/fix/240 Add velocityControlImplementationType option to gazebo_yarp_controlboard plugin

Add velocityControlImplementationType option to gazebo_yarp_controlboard plugin This option permits to switch between using a velocity PID for the Velocity Control
Mode (what has been implemented until now) or the use of an integrator that integrates
the velocity reference and then uses the position low level PID.

The setting is now optional and if not present will default to direct_velocity_pid, but
it will be compulsory in gazebo-yarp-plugins 4.x .

Merge pull request #500 from robotology/fix-rs-426 Avoid to append GAZEBO_CXX_FLAGS to CMAKE_CXX_FLAGS
[plugins][controlboard] Change invalid joint name from 'invalid' to 'gyp_invalid' in BaseCouplingHandler::getCoupledJointName() to avoid naming clashes

Avoid to append GAZEBO_CXX_FLAGS to CMAKE_CXX_FLAGS GAZEBO_CXX_FLAGS was added to CMAKE_CXX_FLAGS in https://github.com/robotology/gazebo-yarp-plugins/pull/190
to support compilation against Gazebo 6 that required C++11, and unfortunately since then Gazebo did not switch to a modern
way of specifying C++ standard requirement in consuming libraries. Now that YARP requires C++14, passing GAZEBO_CXX_FLAGS 
(that contains -std=c++11) basically bypass the CMake logic to compute the correct C++ standard with which to compile the plugins,
and forces to compile them with C++11. 

As the only reason for which GAZEBO_CXX_FLAGS was added to CMAKE_CXX_FLAGS was to enable C++11 support, and as that is already 
passed as a requirement by YARP, I think we can just remove it.

Related SDFormat PR: https://github.com/osrf/sdformat/pull/251 .

Merge pull request #485 from robotology/fix-downstream Avoid useless linking in gazebo_yarp_singleton
fixup

Avoid useless linking in gazebo_yarp_singleton `${YARP_LIBRARIES}` has the peculiar behavior that the contained targets depends on the arguments passed
`find_package(YARP ...)` in this project. In particular, if (and only if) `GAZEBO_YARP_PLUGINS_HAS_OPENCV` is enabled,
then  also the `YARP::YARP_cv` component of yarp is included, that is not required at all. 

For this reason, it is better to just link the libraries we actually depend on, otherwise it will be impossible to use `gazebo_yarp_singleton` 
in a downstream project that do not have the  `YARP::YARP_cv` target defined.
Merge pull request #484 from robotology/optional-opencv Make OpenCV optional again

Make OpenCV optional again OpenCV has always been optional for gazebo-yarp-plugins,
but it was made a required dependency (transitevly by depending on YARP's cv
component) in  https://github.com/robotology/gazebo-yarp-plugins/pull/481 .
This commit makes the OpenCV dependency optional again.

Adding contact loadcell array plugin preliminary working code Implemented as a model plugin (design decision explained in documentation of the plugin) Gets the arbitrary location of load cells with respect to the frame at the link origin
Reads the contact forces and torques at the gazebo collision level through a gazebo ContactSensor plugin
Finds an equivalent wrench acting at the CG of the specified link (location CG, rotation link origin frame)
Transforms the equivalent wrench to the origin of the specified link
Maps the equivalent wrench to an array of contact normal forces acting at the load cell locations

The mapping problem is an infinite solution problem and is done using a pseudo-inverse to get the
results with the minimized norm.

This model plugin in its current version assumes a single collision element per link
This model plugin in its current version handles only one link with a plugin instance (multiple links cannot be specified per plugin)
The collision name should be set to the {link_name}_collision in the contact sensor added to the specific link in the urdf/sdf

Merge pull request #322 from traversaro/addThreeParamSetRefTorques [controlboard] Add three-parameters variant of setRefTorques

Changed how joint control is managed. Until now gazebo messages were sent to gazebo using Gazebo publish/subscribe topic.

With this change, we integrate directly the gazebo PIDs inside the code and we only command Force (or torque) to the joint.

yarp configuration values (such as gazeboYarpPluginsRobotName , or

configuration file. In this way the user can either ignore them,
either use them using the ${variableName} syntax, either overwriting
them specifyng explicit value for them in the configuration files.
